{
    "word": "Twit",
    "definitions": [
        "To vex by bringing to notice, or reminding of, a fault, defect, misfortune, or the like; to revile; to reproach; to upbraid; to taunt; as, he twitted his friend of falsehood."
    ],
    "examples": [
        "This these scoffers twitted the Christians with.",
        "Aesop minds men of their errors, without twitting them for what is amiss."
    ],
    "etymology": "[OE. atwiten, AS. to reproach, blame; aet at + w to reproach, blame; originally, to observe, see, hence, to observe what is wrong (cf. the meanings of E. animadvert; akin to G. verweisen to censure, OHG. firw, Goth. fraweitan to avenge, L. videre to see. See Vision, Wit.]"
}